Copilot Instructions for Android Engineers & General Programming

General Programming Guidelines

Use clear and descriptive names for variables, functions, and classes.

Follow SOLID principles wherever applicable.

Write self-documenting code; comments only for complex logic.

Use consistent formatting and indentation.

Prefer immutable structures and avoid unnecessary state mutation.

Avoid hard-coded values; use constants or configuration files.

Handle exceptions gracefully; prefer try-catch or Result/sealed classes rather than crashing.

Write code that is testable; separate concerns for easier unit testing.

Prefer functional constructs (map, filter, reduce) when they improve readability.


Android Specific Guidelines

Write code in Kotlin by default.

Use MVVM architecture or recommended architecture patterns.

Leverage Jetpack libraries: LiveData, ViewModel, Room, Navigation, WorkManager.

Avoid deprecated Android APIs.

Keep methods short and modular; prioritize readability.

Add comments for non-trivial logic, but avoid excessive commenting.

Prefer coroutines over AsyncTask or raw threads.


UI Components

Use ConstraintLayout by default unless simpler layouts suffice.

Prefer Material Components for buttons, dialogs, text fields, etc.

Use ViewBinding or DataBinding; avoid findViewById.

Use Navigation Component for fragment navigation.

Avoid hard-coded strings; use strings.xml.


Networking & Data

Use Retrofit + Kotlin Serialization/Moshi for network calls.

Use Room for local storage.

Wrap network/database calls in Result/sealed classes.

Use Flow or LiveData for reactive data streams.


AI Generation Guidelines

Generate concise, readable, and idiomatic Kotlin/Java code.

Avoid generating unnecessary boilerplate or empty classes.

Suggest extension functions, sealed classes, or data classes when appropriate.

Prefer composition over inheritance.

Suggest unit tests for complex logic.

Avoid suggesting deprecated APIs or insecure patterns.


Avoid

Avoid using !!; prefer safe calls (?.) or explicit error handling.

Avoid blocking the main thread.

Avoid repeating code; suggest refactoring into functions or extensions.

Avoid hard-coded dimensions, colors, or strings in Android projects.


Optional Enhancements

Suggest Kotlin DSL or extension functions for repetitive tasks.

Suggest Compose equivalents if project uses Jetpack Compose.

Recommend design patterns when appropriate for readability or maintainability.



